# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillization-of-korean
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Among the various ALA-LC romanization systems is a romanization system for the Korean language.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] It was promulgated by and named for the American Library Association (ALA) and Library of Congress (LC).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] It was significantly revised in 2009 and received a minor revision in 2025.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] It is based on the McCune–Reischauer (MR) romanization system, which was published in 1939.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] ALA-LC is meant for use in organizing and retrieving materials in libraries.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] ALA-LC follows McCune–Reischauer (MR) except for exceptions listed in its documentation.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Hyphens are used in two-character Sino-Korean given names (or pseudonyms) of people if those names are preceded by family names.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Given names of native Korean origin or that have three or more characters are not hyphenated.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Do not capitalize the second particle after the hyphen.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Assume the initial "ㄹ" in personal names is always pronounced.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Romanize it as "r", except for names of Western origin; in which case use either "r" or "l" depending on what the Western name does.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The family name 이; 리; 李; 異 is always rendered "Yi".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Multiple syllable family names are rendered without hyphens.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Family names that are a combination of two family names should have a space between those two family names.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Buddhist religious or posthumous names are not hyphenated.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Official titles and honorifics (including 씨, with some exceptions) should have a space between them and the rest of the name.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Titles and terms of address should be capitalized.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Geographical and architectural features (like rivers, mountains, roads, and buildings) should not have a hyphen or space before the generic term at the end.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Apply assimilation in the name, even for the generic term.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Company names should have spacing applied, generally between general terms, and each spaced out element should be capitalized.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Word divisions are determined by following a set of rules, that in general separate by parts of speech.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] When in doubt, refer to dictionaries approved by the LC.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] If still in doubt or if sources differ, prefer to separate.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The rules of ALA-LC for Korean do not account for every instance of romanized text, and subjective variations are possible, particularly on issues of word division.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] This subjectivity can hurt consistency and thus retrieval of information.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Thus, a number of organizations have developed additional tables and lists of common terms in certain spellings.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] For example, with the 2009 revision of ALA-LC for Korean, the Library of Congress published a spreadsheet of common terms and their standardized romanizations.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Like MR, the ALA-LC system reflects the pronunciation of words in its spelling.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Because pronunciation can vary, the system designates several standard dictionaries as references for pronunciation.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] A number of automated tools implement the system.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] These systems do not automatically account for word division.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Two systems are given in the ALA-LC documentation.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The first is BIBFRAME ScriptShifter by the Library of Congress.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] It has two different modes for romanizing Korean: Korean and Korean for people names (with surnames).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] It was developed by Hyoungbae Lee, a Korean studies librarian at Princeton University.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] McCune–Reischauer (MR) was first published in 1939.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The new South Korean government adopted the system in 1948.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The first official LC guidelines for cataloging Korean-language materials was the 1957 *Preliminary Rules and Manual for Cataloging Chinese, Japanese and Korean Materials*.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The LC began to catalogue its Korean-language materials the following year.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The guidelines were revised in 1967 with the *Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules* (AACR1) and in 1978 with AACR2.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 1979, the LC, Online Computer Library Center (OCLC), and Research Libraries Group (RLG) began making machine-readable bibliographic records for East Asian materials.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 1987, the OCLC began the CJK (Chinese, Japanese, and Korean) Cataloguing Project.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Around this time, the Council on East Asian Libraries (CEAL), particularly via its suborganization the Committee on Korean Materials (CKM), worked on various related projects to cataloguing East Asian materials, such as the *Handbook for Korean Studies Librarianship Outside of Korea*.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The ALA-LC romanization tables, including that for Korean, were first promulgated in 1997.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] ALA-LC romanization for Korean has long been controversial and subject to criticism.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 2006, Kim SungKyung argued that confusion about the system was visible in the many mistakes in its application.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The breves used in the system are not reflected in standard keyboards, and are sometimes rendered incorrectly in digitized materials.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Scholar Chris Doll wrote in 2017 that many online search engines drop diacritics from search terms, leading to poorer quality results.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] MR's reflection of pronunciation rules that are not reflected in Hangul itself are explicitly meant for ease of use by non-Koreans.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Korean speakers reportedly often find such pronunciation spellings confusing.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Scholar Jung-ran Park argued that most users of libraries looking for Korean studies materials will have some familiarity with Korean, making MR less useful to them.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Furthermore, the system renders the names of people in a way that most Koreans do not.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] ALA-LC recommends that all Korean names are written according to its rules and not according to personal preferred spelling.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] For example, it renders the surname "이" as "Yi", but around 95% of Koreans spell it "Lee".
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 2004, CKM members met with the LC to discuss revisions to the ALA-LC romanization for Korean.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] LC established a task force to this end.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In March 2008, it began applying its revised system, with general use scheduled for October 2009.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Joy Kim argued in 2009 that updates were seen as improvements but still inadequate.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] For example, hyphens were kept in given names despite requests to remove them.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 2007, the Research Libraries Information Network (RLIN) of RLG began merging with the systems of OCLC.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] The two systems had maintained separate rules around spacing, and they needed to be unified.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] To this end, CEAL organized a panel on the topic in 2008.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 2000, the government of South Korea promulgated its Revised Romanization system, which has since become widely adopted in South Korea.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Whether libraries should adopt this system instead is a subject of debate.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Scholar Joy Kim argued that, while the system has features that make it appealing to Koreans, it is inadequate for use by librarians.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Namely, it allows for flexibility (particularly in word divisions) in ways that are ill-suited for use in libraries.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] In 2017, Doll advocated for switching to RR.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/ala-lc-romanization-for-korean] Doll argued that the LC had previously lagged behind the rest of the world in adopting the pinyin romanization system for Chinese, although it did eventually switch over beginning in 1997, as fewer and fewer people could use the previous system, Wade–Giles.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/cyrillization-of-korean] The **Cyrillization of Korean** is the transcribing and transliterating the Korean language into the Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/cyrillization-of-korean] The main cyrillization system in use is the Kontsevich system (Russian: Систе́ма Конце́вича, romanized: *Sistema Kontsevicha*, IPA: [sʲɪˈsʲtʲemə kɐnˈt͡sɛvʲɪt͡ɕə]).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/cyrillization-of-korean] The Kontsevich system was created by the Soviet-Russian scholar Lev Kontsevich (Russian: Лев Конце́вич, IPA: [ˈlʲef kɐnˈtsɛvʲɪtɕ]) in the 1950s based on the earlier transliteration system designed by Aleksandr Kholodovich (Russian: Алекса́ндр Холодо́вич, IPA: [ɐlʲɪkˈsandr xəlɐˈdovʲɪtɕ]).
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/cyrillization-of-korean] Cyrillization systems for Korean were developed domestically in both North Korea (where it has been proposed to replace the current script in the past) and South Korea; Kontsevich carried out work on the systemization of these rules.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/cyrillization-of-korean] In contrast with some systems of Romanization of Korean, the transcription is based primarily on the pronunciation of a word, rather than on its spelling.
[src:cyrillization-of-korean/cyrillization-of-korean] Some letters are transcribed differently in the middle of a word when following certain other letters.
